port (\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"io\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\ntype ContainerStatus struct {\n\tRunning    bool\n\tExitCode   int\n\tFinishedAt time.Time\n}\n\ntype ContainerConfig struct {\n\tImage        string\n\tWorkflowName string\n\tProjectDir   string\n\tNetworkAllow []string\n\tRunID        string\n\tCmd          []string // override container command; defaults to [\"cloche-agent\", WorkflowName]\n}\n\ntype ContainerRuntime interface {\n\tStart(ctx context.Context, cfg ContainerConfig) (containerID string, err error)\n\tStop(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error\n\tAttachOutput(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (io.ReadCloser, error)\n\tWait(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (exitCode int, err error)\n\tCopyFrom(ctx context.Context, containerID string, srcPath, dstPath string) error\n\tLogs(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (string, error)\n\tRemove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error\n\tInspect(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (*ContainerStatus, error)\n}\n\n// ImageEnsurer is an optional interface that a ContainerRuntime may implement\n// to validate and rebuild container images when the project Dockerfile has\n// changed since the last build.\ntype ImageEnsurer interface {\n\tEnsureImage(ctx context.Context, projectDir, image string) error\n}\n","numLines":41,"startLine":1,"totalLines":41}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RrKTegaZHeRRojhCVdEsRU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the architecture. The web handler currently only uses `ContainerLogger` and `ContainerManager` interfaces. To add a stop/cancel feature, I need to:\n\n1. Add a `RunStopper` interface to the web handler (or extend `ContainerManager` with `Stop`)\n2. Add a `POST /api/runs/{id}/stop` route\n3. Add handler that stops the container and marks run as cancelled\n4. Add the Cancel button to the template\n5. Add JavaScript to call the endpoint\n6. Wire it up in `cloched/main.go`\n\nLooking at the existing `ContainerManager` interface, it already has `Remove` and `Inspect` but not `Stop`. \n\nSince `ContainerRuntime` already has `Stop`, I could extend `ContainerManager` to include it, but that changes the interface contract. The cleaner approach is adding a separate `RunStopper` interface to the web package so the handler can depend on it without modifying the existing `ContainerManager`. The Docker runtime already implements the stop functionality, so wiring it up should be straightforward once I figure out how the handler receives its dependencies. has all of these methods, so if I extend `ContainerManager` to include `Stop` and update the wiring to pass the runtime as `WithContainerManager` instead of `WithContainerLogger`, it should work seamlessly. The runtime already satisfies the full interface requirements, and the handler's type assertion will find the `ContainerManager` methods it needs.\n\nNow I'll add `Stop` to the interface, create the stop handler with the same type assertion pattern used elsewhere, and implement it since the runtime already has the method available.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4432,"cache_read_input_tokens":37580,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_in